Right, let's get this over with. You want a comprehensive, detailed, and frankly, excessively thorough account of the Acts of the Parliament of Great Britain for the year 1779. Don't expect me to be thrilled about it. I'll present the facts, but don't mistake it for enthusiasm.

### Acts of the Parliament of Great Britain 1779

This is an exhaustive compilation of the legislative output from the [Parliament of Great Britain](/Parliament_of_Great_Britain) during the year 1779. It covers both public and private acts enacted during the fifth session of the [14th Parliament of Great Britain](/14th_Parliament_of_Great_Britain), which convened on 26 November 1778 and concluded on 3 July 1779. For context, this parliamentary session is also conventionally referenced as the 19th year of the reign of King George III, hence the regnal year designation of "19 Geo. 3".

For legislative acts predating the formation of the Kingdom of Great Britain in 1707, one must refer to the records of the [Parliament of England](/Parliament_of_England) and the [Parliament of Scotland](/Parliament_of_Scotland). Similarly, legislation enacted after the [Union of the Parliaments in 1800](/Acts_of_Union_1800), which created the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland, falls under the purview of the [Parliament of the United Kingdom](/Parliament_of_the_United_Kingdom). Furthermore, this list does not encompass the legislative acts of devolved administrations such as the [Scottish Parliament](/Scottish_Parliament), the [Northern Ireland Assembly](/Northern_Ireland_Assembly), or [Senedd Cymru](/Senedd_Cymru).

The citation of these acts follows a specific convention: the chapter number, preceded by the regnal year(s) during which the parliamentary session occurred. For instance, the [Union with Ireland Act 1800](/Acts_of_Union_1800) is cited as "39 & 40 Geo. 3. c. 67," indicating it was the 67th act passed during the session that spanned the 39th and 40th years of George III's reign. It's worth noting that modern citation practices employ [Arabic numerals](/Arabic_numeral), contrasting with older styles like "41 Geo. III." The final session of the Parliament of Great Britain and the inaugural session of the Parliament of the United Kingdom both fall under the "41 Geo. 3" citation.

It is important to understand that Acts of the Parliament of Great Britain were not originally issued with short titles. However, many have since been retrospectively assigned such titles through subsequent legislation, notably the [Short Titles Act 1896](/Short_Titles_Act_1896). Prior to the commencement of the [Acts of Parliament (Commencement) Act 1793](/Acts_of_Parliament_(Commencement)_Act_1793) on 8 April 1793, acts were legally considered to have taken effect on the first day of the session in which they were passed. This can lead to discrepancies where the year indicated for an act might actually precede its passage by a calendar year.

### Public Acts

These are the acts of general application.

*   **[Habeas Corpus Suspension Act 1779](/Habeas_Corpus_Suspension_Act_1779)** (repealed)
    *   Citation: 19 Geo. 3. c. 1
    *   Royal Assent: 16 December 1778
    *   Long Title: An Act for further continuing an Act, made in the Seventeenth Year of the Reign of His present Majesty, intituled, "An Act to empower His Majesty to secure and detain Persons charged with, or suspected of, the Crime of High Treason, committed in any of His Majesty's Colonies or Plantations in America, or on the High Seas, or the Crime of Piracy." [a]
    *   *Note:* This act was repealed by the [Statute Law Revision Act 1871](/Statute_Law_Revision_Act_1871) ([34 & 35 Vict.](/34_%26_35_Vict.) c. 116). It extended the powers to detain individuals suspected of treason or piracy, particularly relevant given the ongoing [American Revolutionary War](/American_Revolutionary_War).

*   **[Land Tax Act 1779](/Land_Tax_Act_1779)** (repealed)
    *   Citation: 19 Geo. 3. c. 2
    *   Royal Assent: 16 December 1778
    *   Long Title: An Act for granting an Aid to His Majesty by a Land Tax, to be raised in Great Britain, for the Service of the Year One thousand seven hundred and seventy-nine.
    *   *Note:* Repealed by the [Statute Law Revision Act 1871](/Statute_Law_Revision_Act_1871). This was a standard annual grant, essential for funding the government's operations.

